const Q_PHYSICS_1989=[{"id": "objective>Physics>1989>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is a set of vectors?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">force, mass and moment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">acceleration, velocity and moment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mass, weight and density</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mass, volume and density</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In physics, a vector is a quantity that has both magnitude (a numerical value) and direction. Examples include displacement, velocity, and force. Think of a car moving at 60 mph north. The 60 mph is the magnitude, and \"north\" is the direction. <br/>  <br/> A scalar is a quantity that has only magnitude. It does not have a direction. Examples include mass, temperature, and speed. A temperature of 25&#176;C doesn't have a direction associated with it. <br/>  <br/> - Acceleration is a vector because it describes the rate of change of velocity, which has direction. <br/>  <br/> - Velocity is a vector as it specifies both the speed and direction of an object. <br/>  <br/> - Moment (or torque) is a vector because it's a rotational force that has both a magnitude and a direction of rotation (e.g., clockwise or counter-clockwise). <br/>  <br/> Since all three are vector quantities, this is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "SCALARS AND VECTORS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The magnitude of the resultant of two mutually perpendicular forces, F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> and F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> is 13 N, if the magnitude of F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> is 5 N, what is the magnitude of F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.6 N</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6.0 N</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">12.0 N</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">18.0 N</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Resultant magnitude: R = 13 N <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> ​= 5 N <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> ​= ? <br/>  <br/> R = &radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> + F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>&nbsp;</span> <br/>  <br/> 13 = &radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">5<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> + F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>&nbsp;</span> <br/>  <br/> 13<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 5<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> + F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> <br/>  <br/> 169 = 25 + F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 169 - 25 <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 144 <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = &radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">144&nbsp;</span> <br/>  <br/> ∴ F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 12.0 N</div>", "topic": "EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES: CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Two points on a velocity time-graph have coordinates (5 s, 10 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>) and (20 s, 20 <span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>). Calculate the mean acceleration between the two points</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.67 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.83 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.50 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.00 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span></div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">a</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">Δv<hr size=\"1\" />Δt</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> - v<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />t<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> - t<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">a</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">20 - 10<hr size=\"1\" />20 - 5</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">a</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">10<hr size=\"1\" />15</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">a</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">2<hr size=\"1\" />3</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ a = 0.67 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span></div>", "topic": "MOTION: LINEAR MOTION"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A thin film of liquid is trapped between two glass plates. The force required to pull the plates apart will increase if the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">surface tension of the liquid is reduced</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perpendicular distance between the plates is increased</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">area of the liquid surface in contact with the plates is increased</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pressure of the air is decreased</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The force required to pull two glass plates apart with a thin liquid film between them will increase if the area of the liquid surface in contact with the plates is increased. <br/> Here's a breakdown of the physics behind this phenomenon: <br/> When a thin film of liquid is trapped between two glass plates, the liquid film forms a concave meniscus (a curved surface) at the edges due to the strong adhesive forces between the liquid and the glass. This concave curvature results in the pressure inside the liquid film being lower than the atmospheric pressure outside. <br/> The force holding the plates together is a result of this pressure difference. The force (F) is calculated as the pressure difference (ΔP) multiplied by the contact area (A) of the liquid film on the plates. The pressure difference itself is directly proportional to the liquid's surface tension (T) and inversely proportional to the radius of curvature (r) of the meniscus. <br/> The formula for this force can be expressed as:  <br/> F = 2TA/d​ <br/> where T is the surface tension, A is the area of the plates in contact with the liquid, and d is the perpendicular distance between the plates. <br/>  <br/> C) area of the liquid surface in contact with the plates is increased: As the formula shows (F ∝  A), an increase in the area (A) of the liquid film in contact with the plates directly leads to an increase in the required force.</div>", "topic": "FLUIDS AT REST AND IN MOTION: SURFACE TENSION"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A block-and-tackle system is used to lift a load of 20 N through a vertical height of 10 m. if the efficiency of the system is 40%, how much work is done against friction?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">80 J</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">120 J</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">300 J</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">500 J</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">out</span> = Load × height <br/>  <br/> W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">out</span> = 20 × 10 = 200 J <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">E</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">out</span><hr size=\"1\" />W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">100%</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">40%</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">200<hr size=\"1\" />W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">100%</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">40<hr size=\"1\" />100</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">200<hr size=\"1\" />W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">0.4</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">200<hr size=\"1\" />W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> 0.4W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span> = 200 <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">200<hr size=\"1\" />0.4</td></tr></table></div> <br/> W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span> = 500 J <br/>  <br/> Work lost to friction = Input work – Output work: <br/>  <br/> ∴ W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">friction</span> ​= W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">in</span>​ − W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">out</span>​ = 500 - 200 = 300 J</div>", "topic": "SIMPLE MACHINES : EFFICIENCY OF MACHINES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following devices are used to measure pressure? i. Aneroid barometer. ii. hydrometer. iii. hygrometer. iv. manometer.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">i and iii</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ii and iii</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">iii and iv</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">i and iv</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct option is i and iv. The aneroid barometer and manometer are both used to measure pressure. <br/>  <br/> Aneroid Barometer (i): A barometer measures atmospheric pressure. The aneroid type uses a sealed, partially evacuated metal capsule that expands or contracts with changes in air pressure. This movement is linked to a dial that displays the pressure reading. <br/>  <br/> Manometer (iv): A manometer is used to measure the pressure of a gas or liquid, often within a closed container. It typically consists of a U-shaped tube containing a liquid (like water or mercury) where the pressure is determined by the height difference of the liquid columns. <br/>  <br/> Incorrect Options <br/> Hydrometer (ii): This device measures the relative density (or specific gravity) of liquids. It's a weighted glass float that sinks to a certain depth depending on the liquid's density. <br/>  <br/> Hygrometer (iii): This instrument measures the humidity, which is the amount of water vapor in the air.</div>", "topic": "PRESSURE: ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A piece of wood of mass 40 g and uniform cross-sectional area of 2 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> floats upright in water. The length of the wood immersed is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">30 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">40 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">20 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2 cm</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The length of the wood immersed in water is 20 cm. <br/>  <br/> This is a problem based on the principle of flotation. This principle states that a floating object displaces a volume of fluid whose weight is equal to the object's own weight. <br/>  <br/> Weight of object = Weight of displaced fluid <br/>  <br/> This can be simplified to: <br/>  <br/> Mass of object = Mass of displaced fluid <br/>  <br/> The mass of the displaced water is equal to the mass of the piece of wood, which is given as 40 g. <br/>  <br/> The mass of the displaced water can also be expressed as: <br/>  <br/> Mass = Density × Volume <br/>  <br/> The volume of the displaced water is the volume of the portion of the wood that is submerged. Since the wood has a uniform cross-sectional area, this volume can be calculated as: <br/>  <br/> Volume (V) = Cross-sectional Area (A) × Length Immersed (L) <br/>  <br/> We know that: <br/>  <br/> Mass of wood = Density of water × Volume of displaced water <br/>  <br/> 40 g = (ρ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">water</span>​) × (A) × (L) <br/>  <br/> The density of water is approximately 1 g/cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span>. <br/>  <br/> 40 g = (1 g/cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span>) × (2 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>) × (L) <br/>  <br/> Now, solve for L: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">40<hr size=\"1\" />1 × 2</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">∴</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">40​<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">20</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">cm</td></tr></table></div></div>", "topic": "FLUIDS AT REST AND IN MOTION: LIQUIDS AT REST"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The pressure on the gas of constant gas thermometer at the ice point is 325 mm of mercury and at the steam point is 875 mm of mercury. Find the temperature when the pressure of the gas is 190 mm of mercury</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">30 K</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">248 K</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">300 K</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">3003 K</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">C - 0<hr size=\"1\" />100</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">190 - 325<hr size=\"1\" />875 - 325</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">C<hr size=\"1\" />100</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-135<hr size=\"1\" />550</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">C</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-135<hr size=\"1\" />550</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> C = -24.55°C <br/>  <br/> ∴ The temperature when the pressure of the gas is 190 mm of mercury  <br/>  <br/> = -24.55 + 273 = 248.45 K</div>", "topic": "GAS LAWS: CALCULATIONS OF GAS LAWS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A column of air 10.0 cm long is trapped in a tube at 27°C. What is the length of the volume at 100°C?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">12.4 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">13.7 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">18.5 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">37.0 cm</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Initial length L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 10.0 cm (which is proportional to volume since area is constant) <br/>  <br/> Initial temperature T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 27°C = 27 + 273 = 300 K <br/>  <br/> Final temperature T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 100°C = 100 + 273 = 373 K <br/>  <br/> We need to find the final length L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>​. <br/>  <br/> Using Charles's Law: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">​​</td></tr></table></div> <br/> Since volume V is proportional to length L (because cross-sectional area is constant), we can write: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">10<hr size=\"1\" />300</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />373</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">10<hr size=\"1\" />300</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">373</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3730<hr size=\"1\" />300</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 12.43 cm</div>", "topic": "GAS LAWS: CALCULATIONS OF GAS LAWS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A mass of gas at 7°C and 70 cm of mercury has a volume of 1200 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span>. Determine its volume at 27°C and pressure of 75 cm of mercury.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1200 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1378 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">4320 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">4629 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span></div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> ​= 70 cmHg <br/>  <br/> V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 1200 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> <br/>  <br/> T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 7°C = 7 + 273 = 280 K <br/>  <br/> P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 75 cmHg <br/>  <br/> T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 27°C = 27 + 273 = 300 K <br/>  <br/> V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = ? <br/>  <br/> To determine the volume of the gas at 27∘C and a pressure of 75 cm Hg, we use the combined gas law: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span>V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">P<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">70 × 1200<hr size=\"1\" />280</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">75 × V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />300</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">70 × 1200 × 300<hr size=\"1\" />280 × 75</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">25,200,000<hr size=\"1\" />2,100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 1200 cm<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span></div>", "topic": "GAS LAWS: CALCULATIONS OF GAS LAWS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An electric heater is used to melt a block of ice of mass 1.5 kg. If the heater is powered by a 12 V battery and a current of 20 A flows through the coil, calculate the time taken to melt the block of ice at 0°C. [specific latent heat of fusion of ice = 336 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> Jkg<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>]</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">76.0 min</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">35.0 min</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">21.0 min</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.9 min</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To calculate the time taken to melt the block of ice using the electric heater, we need to determine the amount of energy required to melt the ice and then relate it to the power supplied by the heater. <br/>  <br/> Given: <br/>  <br/> Mass of ice, m = 1.5 kg <br/>  <br/> Specific latent heat of fusion of ice, L<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">f</span> = 336 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> J/kg <br/>  <br/> Voltage, V = 12 V <br/>  <br/> Current, I = 20 A <br/>  <br/> The energy H needed to melt ice is given by: <br/>  <br/> H = mL<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">f</span> ​ <br/>  <br/> Substitute the values: <br/>  <br/> H = 1.5 × 336 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> = 1.5 × 336000 = 504000 J <br/>  <br/> The power P delivered by the heater is: <br/>  <br/> P = VI <br/>  <br/> P = 12 × 20 = 240 W <br/>  <br/> The time t is related to energy and power by: <br/>  <br/> H = Pt <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">t</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">H<hr size=\"1\" />P</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">504000<hr size=\"1\" />240</td></tr></table></div> <br/> t = 2100 s <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">∴</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">t</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">2100<hr size=\"1\" />60</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">mins</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">35.0</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">mins</td></tr></table></div></div>", "topic": "HEAT TRANSFER: LATENT HEAT OF FUSION"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the kinetic theory of gases, temperature is a</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">form of energy and is proportional to the total kinetic energy of the molecules</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">form of energy and is proportional to the average kinetic energy of the molecules</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">physical property and is proportional to the total kinetic energy of the molecules</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">physical property and is proportional to the average kinetic energy of the molecules</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the kinetic theory of gases, temperature is not a form of energy but a physical property that measures how energetic molecules are. It is directly proportional to the average kinetic energy of the molecules, given by <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">E<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">k</span>‾</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">k<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">B</span>T</td></tr></table></div> <br/> Thus, the correct statement is \"temperature is a physical property and is proportional to the average kinetic energy of the molecules.\" <br/> </div>", "topic": "STRUCTURE OF MATTER AND KINETIC THEORY : KINETIC THEORY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A vibrator of frequency 60 Hz is used in generating transverse stationary waves in a long thin wire, If the average distance between successive nodes on the wire is 45 cm, find the speed of the transverse waves in the wire.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">27 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">54 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">90 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">108 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">f = 60 Hz <br/>  <br/> l = 45 cm = 0.45 m <br/>  <br/> λ = 2l = 2 × 0.45 = 0.90 m  <br/>  <br/> v = fλ = 0.9 × 60  <br/>  <br/> ∴ v = 54 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "topic": "SOUND WAVES: CALCULATIONS ON SOUND WAVES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When the tension in a sonometer wire is doubled, the ratio of the new frequency to the initial frequency is?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">2&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></div></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />2</td></tr></table></div></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">2&nbsp;</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For a vibrating string (like a sonometer wire): <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />2L</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">T<hr size=\"1\" />M</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</span>​​</td></tr></table></div> <br/> where <br/>  <br/> f = frequency, <br/>  <br/> T = tension, <br/>  <br/> L = length, <br/>  <br/> M = mass per unit length. <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 2T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> (Given) <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />2T<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span><hr size=\"1\" />F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">2&nbsp;</span></td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span><hr size=\"1\" />F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">&radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">2&nbsp;</span><hr size=\"1\" />1</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> : F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = &radic;<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;border-top:solid black 1px;\">2&nbsp;</span> : 1</div>", "topic": "SOUND WAVES: CALCULATIONS ON SOUND WAVES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a sound wave in air, the adjacent rarefactions and compressions are separated by a distance of 17 cm. If the velocity of the sound wave is 340 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>. Determine the frequency</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">10 Hz</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">20 Hz</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1000 Hz</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5780 Hz</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">λ = 2L = 2 × 17 = 34 cm <br/>  <br/> λ = 0.34 m <br/>  <br/> v = fλ <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v<hr size=\"1\" />λ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">340<hr size=\"1\" />0.34</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ f = 1000 Hz</div>", "topic": "SOUND WAVES: CALCULATIONS ON SOUND WAVES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Light of wavelength 5000 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-5</span> cm travels in free space with a velocity of 3 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">8</span> ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>. What is its wavelength in glass of refractive index 1.5?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">3333 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">5000 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6666 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">7500 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> cm</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The refractive index n is given by: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">n</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">λ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">0</span><hr size=\"1\" />λ</td></tr></table></div> <br/> where: <br/>  <br/> λ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">0</span>​ = wavelength in free space (vacuum/air), <br/>  <br/> λ = wavelength in the medium (glass), <br/>  <br/> n = refractive index of the medium. <br/>  <br/> So, <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">λ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">λ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">0</span><hr size=\"1\" />n</td></tr></table></div> <br/> n = 1.5 <br/>  <br/> λ<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">0</span> = 5.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−5</span> cm <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">λ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">5.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−5</span><hr size=\"1\" />1.5</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ λ = 3.333 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−5</span> cm = 3333 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−8</span> cm</div>", "topic": "LIGHT WAVES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The magnification of the image of an object placed in front of a convex mirror is <span style=\"position: relative;left:3px;top:-7px; font-size:15px;\">1</span>/<span style=\"position:relative;left:-3px;top:7px;font-size:15px;\">3</span>. If the radius of curvature of the mirror is 24 cm, what is the distance between its object and its image?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">8 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">16 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">24 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">64 cm</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">R<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">24<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">12</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">cm</td></tr></table></div> <br/> For convex mirror, f = −12cm <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">M</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />3</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">M</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v<hr size=\"1\" />u</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />3</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v<hr size=\"1\" />u</td></tr></table></div> <br/> u = 3v <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />u</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />-12</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />3v</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />12</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1 + 3<hr size=\"1\" />3v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />12</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">4<hr size=\"1\" />3v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> -3v = 12 × 4 <br/>  <br/> -v = 4 × 4 <br/>  <br/> -v = 16 <br/>  <br/> v = -16 cm <br/>  <br/> So, image distance v = 16 cm (negative → behind mirror, which is correct for convex). <br/>  <br/> Then object distance: <br/>  <br/> u = 3v = 3 × 16 = 48 cm <br/>  <br/> The distance between the object and the image is: <br/>  <br/> Distance = |u| + |v| = 48 + 16 = 64 cm <br/>  <br/> (Since the object is in front and the image is behind, the total separation is the sum of their absolute distances from the mirror.)</div>", "topic": "LIGHT WAVES: REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE AND CURVED SURFACES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The plane mirrors in a kaleidoscope are usually placed</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at an angle of 60°</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">parallel to one another</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perpendicular to one another</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at an angle of 45°</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In a kaleidoscope, the plane mirrors are arranged to create multiple reflections that produce symmetrical patterns. The typical arrangement is at an angle of 60° <br/> This is the standard configuration for a kaleidoscope. Three mirrors are often placed at 60° to each other to form an equilateral triangle, which generates hexagonal symmetry and repetitive patterns.</div>", "topic": "LIGHT WAVES: REFLECTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE AND CURVED SURFACES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A far sighted person cannot see objects that are less than 100 cm away. If this person wants to read a book at 25 cm, what type and focal length of lens does he need?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">convex, 20 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concave, 20 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">convex, 33 cm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concave, 33 cm</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">u = 25 cm <br/>  <br/> For a virtual image on the same side, v = -100 cm <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />u</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />25</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />-100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />25</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">4-1<hr size=\"1\" />100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3<hr size=\"1\" />100</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">100<hr size=\"1\" />3</td></tr></table></div> <br/> f = 33.33 cm <br/>  <br/> Since the focal length is a positive value, it confirms that a convex (converging) lens is needed, as expected for the correction of far-sightedness.</div>", "topic": "LIGHT WAVES: REFRACTION OF LIGHT THROUGH LENSES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a yellow card is observed through a blue glass, the card would appear.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">black</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">green</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">red</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">white</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To determine the appearance of a yellow card when viewed through a blue glass, we need to consider the colors of light involved. <br/>  <br/> The yellow card appears yellow because it reflects yellow light and absorbs other colors. <br/>  <br/> The blue glass allows only blue light to pass through and absorbs other colors. <br/>  <br/> When white light (which contains all colors) shines on the yellow card: <br/>  <br/> The card reflects yellow light and absorbs other colors. <br/>  <br/> This reflected yellow light then reaches the blue glass. <br/>  <br/> Yellow light is a combination of red and green light. Blue glass absorbs red and green light (since it only transmits blue). <br/>  <br/> Therefore, the yellow light (red + green) is absorbed by the blue glass, and no light is transmitted. <br/>  <br/> As a result, the card will appear black because no light reaches the eye.</div>", "topic": "DISPERSION OF LIGHT AND COLOURS : COLOUR MIXING"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dispersion of light by a glass prism is due to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">different colours of the glass</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">different speeds of the various colours in glass</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">defects in the glass</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">high density of glass</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The dispersion of light by a glass prism occurs because different colors (wavelengths) of light travel at different speeds in the glass. This difference in speed causes each color to refract (bend) by a different amount when entering and exiting the prism. As a result, white light is separated into its constituent colors, forming a spectrum.</div>", "topic": "DISPERSION OF LIGHT AND COLOURS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following pairs is NOT part of the electromagnetic spectrum? i. Radio waves. ii. Beta rays. iii. Gamma rays. iv. Alpha rays</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">i and ii</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">iii and iv</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">i and iii</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ii and iv</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To determine which pair is not part of the electromagnetic spectrum, recall that the electromagnetic spectrum includes: <br/>  <br/> Radio waves <br/>  <br/> Microwaves <br/>  <br/> Infrared <br/>  <br/> Visible light <br/>  <br/> Ultraviolet <br/>  <br/> X-rays <br/>  <br/> Gamma rays <br/>  <br/> Now, analyze the options: <br/>  <br/> Beta rays: These are streams of beta particles (electrons or positrons), which are not electromagnetic waves; they are particles. <br/>  <br/> Alpha rays: These are streams of alpha particles (helium nuclei), which are not electromagnetic waves; they are particles. <br/>  <br/> Thus, both beta rays and alpha rays are not part of the electromagnetic spectrum.</div>", "topic": "ELECTROMAGNETIC SPECTRUM"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Two insulated charged spheres of different sizes and carrying opposite charges are connected together by a metallic conductor. Current will flow from one sphere to the other until both sphere</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">carry the same magnitude and sign of charge</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are at the same potential</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are at the same temperature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are of the same size</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When two insulated charged spheres of different sizes and carrying opposite charges are connected by a metallic conductor, electrons will flow through the conductor until the electric potential of both spheres becomes equal. This is because the conductor allows charge to move to equalize the potential.</div>", "topic": "ELECTROSTATICS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a number of identical small magnets are arranged in a line, the strength of the resultant magnet</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is largest when they are arranged end to end</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is greatest when they are arranged parallel with like poles adjacent to each other</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">depends only on the number of magnets provided they are parallel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is greater when the magnets are arranged on a wooden surface than on a metal surface</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct option is \"is largest when they are arranged end to end.\" <br/>  <br/> The Physics of Combining Magnets <br/> The strength of a magnet's external magnetic field is determined by its design and material. When you arrange multiple magnets, their individual magnetic fields combine to form a resultant magnetic field. To get the strongest possible combined field, the fields of the individual magnets must be aligned and reinforced. <br/>  <br/> End-to-End Arrangement <br/> When identical magnets are arranged end-to-end with opposite poles touching (e.g., North-South, North-South), their magnetic fields align perfectly. The magnetic field lines from one magnet's North pole flow directly into the next magnet's South pole, effectively creating a single, longer magnet. This arrangement concentrates the magnetic field lines and produces a much stronger resultant magnet than the individual parts. <br/>  <br/> Parallel Arrangement <br/> Conversely, if the magnets are arranged side-by-side with like poles adjacent (e.g., North-South beside North-South), their magnetic fields oppose each other. This creates a repulsive force and a weaker, less coherent external magnetic field, as the field lines are pushed away from each other.</div>", "topic": "MAGNETS AND MAGNETIC FIELDS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A bar magnet is most effectively demagnetized by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">placing it in a N - S position and hitting it with a hammer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">subjecting it to an electric current from a battery</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bringing its north pole in contact with the north pole of a very strong magnet</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heating the magnet</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most effective way to demagnetize a bar magnet from the given options is by heating the magnet. <br/>  <br/> <strong>How Demagnetization Works</strong> <br/> The magnetism of a bar magnet comes from the alignment of tiny internal magnetic regions called magnetic domains. In a magnetized state, these domains are aligned in a single direction, giving the magnet a strong external magnetic field. To demagnetize the magnet, this alignment must be destroyed. <br/>  <br/> <strong>Why Heating is Effective</strong> <br/> Heating a magnet provides its domains with thermal energy. As the temperature rises, the atoms and their domains vibrate more and more violently. At a specific temperature known as the Curie temperature, the thermal agitation is so strong that it completely randomizes the orientation of the magnetic domains, causing the magnet to permanently lose its magnetism.</div>", "topic": "MAGNETS AND MAGNETIC FIELDS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The resistance of a 5 m uniform wire of cross-sectional area 0.2 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-6</span> m<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> is 0.425. What is the resistivity of the material of the wire?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.10 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-6</span> Ωm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">4.25 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-6</span> Ωm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.40 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-7</span> Ωm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.70 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> Ωm</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">R = 0.425 Ω <br/>  <br/> L = 5 m <br/>  <br/> A = 0.2 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−6</span> = 2.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−7</span> m<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">R</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">ρL<hr size=\"1\" />A​</td></tr></table></div> <br/> So, <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">ρ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">RA<hr size=\"1\" />L</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">ρ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">0.425 × 2.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−7</span><hr size=\"1\" />5</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ ρ = 1.70 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-8</span> Ωm</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY: RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Three resistors, with substances 250 Ω, 500 Ω and 1 kΩ are connected in series. A 6 V battery is connected to either end of the combination. Calculate the potential difference between the end of the 250 Ω resistor.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.20 V</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.86 V</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.71 V</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">3.43 V</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Given: <br/>  <br/> Resistors: R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 250 Ω, R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 500 Ω, R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> = 1 kΩ = 1000 Ω <br/>  <br/> Battery voltage: V = 6 V <br/>  <br/> All resistors are connected in series. <br/>  <br/> R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">total</span> = R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> + R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> + R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">3</span> = 250 + 500 + 1000 = 1750 Ω <br/>  <br/> Using Ohm's law: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<hr size=\"1\" />R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">total</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">6<hr size=\"1\" />1750</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3<hr size=\"1\" />875 A</td></tr></table></div> <br/> Using Ohm's law for R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span>​: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">(</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3<hr size=\"1\" />875</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">)</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">250</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3 × 250<hr size=\"1\" />875</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">750<hr size=\"1\" />875</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">30<hr size=\"1\" />35</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">6<hr size=\"1\" />7</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">≈</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">0.857 V</td></tr></table></div> <br/> So, the potential difference across the 250 Ω resistor is 0.86 V.</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY : RESISTANCE IN SERIES AND IN PARALLEL"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A calibrated potentiometer is used to measure the e.m.f. of a cell because the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">internal resistance of a cell is small compared with that of the potentiometer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">potentiometer has a linear scale</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">potentiometer takes no current from the cell</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resistance of the potentiometer is less than that of a voltmeter</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A potentiometer measures the emf of a cell by balancing it against a known potential difference. At the null point (when the galvanometer shows zero deflection), no current flows through the cell. <br/>  <br/> This means the cell is measured under open-circuit conditions, so its internal resistance does not cause a voltage drop, and the true emf is obtained.</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY : POTENTIOMETER"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An ammeter of resistance 0.1 Ω has a full-scale deflection of 50 mA. Determine the resultant full-scale deflection of the meter when a shunt of 0.0111 Ω is connected across its terminals.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">400 mA</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">450 mA</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">500 mA</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">550 mA</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span> = 0.1 Ω <br/>  <br/> I<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span> = 50 mA = 0.05 A <br/>  <br/> R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">s</span> = 0.0111 Ω <br/>  <br/> V = IR <br/>  <br/> Since the voltage across the galvanometer = Voltage across the shunt <br/>  <br/> I<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span>R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span> = (I - I<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span>)R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">s</span> <br/>  <br/> 0.05 × 0.1 = (I - 0.05) × 0.0111 <br/>  <br/> 0.005 = 0.0111I - 0.000555 <br/>  <br/> 0.0111I = 0.005 + 0.000555 <br/>  <br/> 0.0111I = 0.005555 <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">0.005555<hr size=\"1\" />0.0111</td></tr></table></div> <br/> I = 0.5 A <br/>  <br/> ∴ I = 500 mA</div>", "topic": "ELECTRIC CELLS: SHUNT AND MULTIPLIER"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The electrochemical equivalent of silver is 0.0012 gC<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span>. If 36.0 g of silver is to be deposited by electrolysis on a surface by passing a steady current for 5.0 mins, the current must be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6000 A</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">100 A</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">10 A</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1 A</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">m = ZIt <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">m<hr size=\"1\" />Zt</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">36<hr size=\"1\" />0.0012 × 5 × 60</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">36<hr size=\"1\" />0.36</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ I = 100 A</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY: ELECTROLYSIS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When a radiation strikes a metal surface, electrons may be ejected from the metal. The maximum kinetic energy which may be acquired by an ejected electron depend on the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">intensity of the radiation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">source of the radiation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wavelength of the radiation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">detection device of the electron</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phenomenon described is the photoelectric effect. According to the photoelectric effect: <br/> The maximum kinetic energy of an ejected electron is given by: <br/> K<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">max</span> = hc - W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">o</span> <br/> where h is Planck's constant, c is the frequency of the incident radiation, and W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">o</span> is the work function of the metal. <br/> The frequency f is related to the wavelength λ by c = fλ ​, so the kinetic energy depends on the wavelength (or frequency) of the radiation. <br/> The intensity of the radiation affects the number of electrons ejected (the photocurrent) but not the maximum kinetic energy of each electron. <br/> The source of the radiation is not directly relevant; what matters is the frequency (or wavelength) of the incident photons. <br/> The detection device does not affect the inherent maximum kinetic energy of the electrons. <br/> Thus, the maximum kinetic energy depends solely on the wavelength (or frequency) of the radiation.</div>", "topic": "ELEMENTARY MODERN PHYSICS : THERMIONIC AND PHOTOELECTRIC EMISSIONS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is TRUE of the particles emitted in radioactive disintegration?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the beta particle is the helium nucleus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the alpha particle is lighter than the beta particle</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the alpha particle is deflected more than the beta particle in a magnetic field</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the beta particle is deflected more than the alpha particle in a magnetic field</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct statement is \"the beta particle is deflected more than the alpha particle in a magnetic field.\" <br/>  <br/> Properties of Radioactive Particles <br/> During radioactive decay, an unstable atomic nucleus emits particles to become more stable. The two main types of particle radiation are alpha and beta particles. <br/> Alpha (α) particle: This is a helium nucleus (<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">4</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>​He). It consists of two protons and two neutrons, giving it a charge of +2e and a relatively large mass. <br/> Beta (β) particle: This is a high-speed electron or positron. It has a charge of -e (or +e) and is extremely light, with a mass that is less than 1/7000th of an alpha particle's mass. <br/>  <br/> Deflection in a Magnetic Field <br/> When a charged particle moves through a magnetic field, it experiences a force that causes it to deflect. The amount of deflection depends on the particle's charge and mass. A particle with a smaller mass-to-charge ratio will be deflected more significantly. <br/>  <br/> Since the beta particle has a much smaller mass than the alpha particle, its mass-to-charge ratio is also much smaller. Therefore, a beta particle is deflected far more easily and to a greater extent than the much heavier alpha particle.</div>", "topic": "ELEMENTARY MODERN PHYSICS : RADIOACTIVITY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eight alpha decays and six beta decays are necessary before an atom of <span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">238</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">92</span>U achieves stability. The final product in the chain has an atomic number of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">70</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">78</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">82</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">90</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">238</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">92</span>U → 8(<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">4</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span>He) + 6(<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">0</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">−1</span>e) + <span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">b</span><span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">a</span>X <br/>  <br/> 92 = (8 × 2) + (6 × -1) + a <br/>  <br/> a = 82 <br/> </div>", "topic": "ELEMENTARY MODERN PHYSICS : ALPHA, BETA AND GAMMA RAYS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An object is placed at 5.6 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span> m in front of a converging lens of focal length 1.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span> m. The image formed is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Real, Erect and magnified</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Virtual, erect and magnified</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Real, inverted and magnified</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Virtual, erect and diminished</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">u = 5.6 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span> m = 5.6 cm <br/>  <br/> f = 1.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span> m = 10 cm <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />f</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />u</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />10</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />5.6</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />10</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />5.6</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />v</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">11<hr size=\"1\" />140</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">140<hr size=\"1\" />11</td></tr></table></div> <br/> v = -12.73 cm <br/>  <br/> So, v is negative, meaning the image is virtual and on the same side as the object. <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">m</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">v<hr size=\"1\" />u</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-12.73<hr size=\"1\" />5.6</td></tr></table></div> <br/> m = - 2.27 <br/>  <br/> Since m is negative, the image is erect. Magnitude is 2.27, so it is magnified.</div>", "topic": "LIGHT WAVES: REFRACTION OF LIGHT THROUGH LENSES"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The function of a 5-A fuse included in a circuit supplying a household refrigerator with power is to keep the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">temperature of the refrigerator low and constant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">keep current supplied to the refrigerator below 5 A</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">voltage supply constant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">current supplies to the refrigeration</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A fuse is a simple yet vital safety device in an electrical circuit. It is a short piece of wire made from a material with a low melting point. A fuse is placed in a circuit so that all the current flowing to an appliance must pass through it. <br/>  <br/> The rating on a fuse (in this case, 5 A) indicates the maximum amount of current that can safely pass through it. If the current for any reason—such as a short circuit or a malfunction—exceeds this limit, the wire inside the fuse heats up, melts, and breaks the circuit. This instantly stops the flow of current, protecting the household appliance (the refrigerator) and the wiring from damage or fire.</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> The fig above shows a uniform circular object, center R and diameter PS. A circular section and Diameter PR is cut from it. if PQRS is a straight line, where is center of gravity of the figure</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Q</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">R</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A point between P and R</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A point between R and S</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The small circular section centered at Q (left of R) is removed, taking mass from the left side of the original circle. The remaining shape is symmetric about the diameter line PQRS, so the centroid lies on that line; because mass is missing on the left, the centroid shifts to the right of the original centre R, i.e. somewhere between R and S.</div>", "topic": "EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES: CENTRE OF GRAVITY AND STABILITY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> A simple pendulum of mass m moves along an arc of a circle radius R in a vertical plane as shown above. What is the work done by gravity in a downward swing through the angle θ to 0 degree</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mgR sinθ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mgR (1 - cosθ)</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mgR</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mgR (1 - sinθ)</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"1989/N7KB23.png\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> From the above diagram, <br/>  <br/> R = H + h - (1) <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">cosθ</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">H<hr size=\"1\" />R</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">-</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\"></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">(2)</td></tr></table></div> <br/> H = Rcosθ - (3) <br/>   <br/> Workdone = Force × distance <br/>  <br/> = Weight × height  <br/>  <br/> = mg × h  <br/>  <br/> = mgh - (4)  <br/>  <br/> But h = R − H (from equation 1) <br/>  <br/> ∴ Workdone = mgh - (4) <br/>   <br/> = mg(R − H)  <br/>  <br/> Since H = Rcosθ (from equation 3) <br/>  <br/> ⇒ Workdone = mg(R − Rcosθ)  <br/>  <br/> = mgR(1 − cosθ) </div>", "topic": "SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> A block of mass m is held in equilibrium against a vertical wall by a horizontal force. If the coefficient of friction between the wall and the block is µ, the minimum value of the horizontal force is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">µmg</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">(1 - µ)mg</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">(1 + µ)mg</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">mg<hr size=\"1\" />µ</td></tr></table></div></div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The horizontal force (F) is equivalent to the normal reaction (R), i.e F = R = mg <br/>  <br/> But The frictional force (F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">r</span>) acting vertically upward = the limiting frictional force (µ) × normal reaction (R) <br/>  <br/> i.e F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">r</span> = µ × R <br/>  <br/> To balance the vertical upward force (F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">r</span>) and vertical downward for (Mg) <br/>  <br/> F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">r</span> = mg  <br/>  <br/> But F<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">r</span> = µR <br/>  <br/> µR = mg (recall R = F) <br/>  <br/> µF = mg <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">∴</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">F</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">mg<hr size=\"1\" />µ</td></tr></table></div></div>", "topic": "MOTION: FRICTION"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> In the fig above W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">1</span> = 200 g, and W<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">2</span> = 450 g. Calculate the extension of the spring per unit load. [g = 10 ms<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−2</span>]</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-5</span> mN<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.5 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-4</span> mN<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6.0 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-3</span> mN<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2.5 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-2</span> mN<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the diagram given in the question <br/>  <br/> Change in length = (6.5 - 5.0) × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−2</span> m <br/>  <br/> Change in force (w<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">g</span>) = (420 - 200) × 10 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−3</span> = 2.5 N (g changed to kg) <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">extension</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">per</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">unit</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">x</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">Δl<hr size=\"1\" />ΔF</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1.5 × 10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−2</span><hr size=\"1\" />2.5</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">6.0</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">×</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">10<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">−3</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">mN<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:-6px;font-size:13px;\">-1</span></td></tr></table></div></div>", "topic": "ELASTICITY : WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND ELASTIC STRINGS"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> The air column as shown above is set into vibration by the turning fork. In this State of resonance, the waves in the air column will be</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stationary and transverse</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stationary and longitudinal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">progressive and transverse</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">progressive and longitudinal</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The type of wave created in this setup is determined by two key factors: the nature of the wave itself and the state of the vibration. <br/>  <br/> Nature of the Wave: The tuning fork produces sound waves, which are longitudinal waves. In a longitudinal wave, particles of the medium (in this case, air) vibrate parallel to the direction of wave propagation. <br/>  <br/> State of the Vibration: The problem mentions a \"state of resonance.\" When resonance occurs in a system like an air column (closed at one end by the water surface), the incident sound waves from the tuning fork interfere with the reflected waves from the water. This interference creates a stationary wave (also known as a standing wave). In a stationary wave, certain points remain fixed (nodes), while others vibrate with maximum amplitude (antinodes). <br/>  <br/> Since the waves are sound waves (longitudinal) and are in a state of resonance (stationary), the correct combination is stationary and longitudinal.</div>", "topic": "SOUND WAVE: RESONANCE"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> In the above circuit diagrams A is the ammeter and V is the voltmeter. Which of the circuits is correct for finding the correct value of the resistance R</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">II</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">III</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">IV</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To measure the resistance R correctly in a circuit: <br/>  <br/> The ammeter (A) must be connected in series with the resistor R, because it measures the current flowing through R. <br/>  <br/> The voltmeter (V) must be connected in parallel across the resistor R, because it measures the potential difference across R. <br/>  <br/> This arrangement ensures the true resistance value can be calculated using Ohm's law: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">R</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<hr size=\"1\" />I</td></tr></table></div> <br/> Therefore, the correct circuit is (I).</div>", "topic": "CURRENT ELECTRICITY"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> Three 2 µF capacitors are arranged as seen in the circuit above. The effective capacitance between E and F is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">0.75 µF</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.33 µF</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">3.00 µF</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">6.00 µF</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For the parallel arrangement: <br/>  <br/> C = 2 µF + 2 µF = 4 µF <br/>  <br/> The effective capacitance between E and F is: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />C<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />2</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">+</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />4</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />C<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">2 + 1<hr size=\"1\" />4</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">1<hr size=\"1\" />C<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">3<hr size=\"1\" />4</td></tr></table></div> <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">C<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">4<hr size=\"1\" />3</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">µF</td></tr></table></div> <br/> ∴ C<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span> = 1.33 µF</div>", "topic": "CAPACITORS : CAPACITORS IN SERIES AND PARALLEL"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> The total power drawn from the cell in the circuit above is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">12 W</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">24 W</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">32 W</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">40 W</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For the parallel connection: <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">R</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">4 × 4<hr size=\"1\" />4 + 4</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">16<hr size=\"1\" />8</td></tr></table></div> <br/> R = 2 Ω <br/>  <br/> The effective resistance: <br/>  <br/> R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span> = 4 + 2 = 6 Ω <br/>  <br/> From Ohm's law, <br/>  <br/> V = IR<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span> <br/>  <br/> So, <br/>  <br/> <div style=\"display:block;position:relative;width:100%;\"><table cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"position: relative;border-collapse:collapse;\"><tr><td style=\"text-align:center;\">I</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">V<hr size=\"1\" />R<span style=\"margin: 0;padding:0;position:relative;top:4px;font-size:13px;\">T</span></td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">=</td><td style=\"text-align:center;\">12<hr size=\"1\" />6</td></tr></table></div> <br/> I = 2 A <br/>  <br/> The total power drawn from the cell in the circuit above is: <br/>  <br/> P = IV = 2 × 12 <br/>  <br/> ∴ P = 24 W</div>", "topic": "ELECTRIC CELLS: ELECTRIC CIRCUIT SERIES AND PARALLEL ARRANGEMENT OF CELLS AND RESISTORS~~ELECTRICAL ENERGY AND POWER"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> The fig above shows a conductor PQ carrying a current I in the direction shown. At a particular position near the conductor is a compass needle K. Neglecting the earth's magnetic field, the compass needle will</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">settle in any direction</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">settle in a fixed direction only if the conductor PQ is a magnetic material</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">settle in a fixed direction WHETHER the conductor PQ is a magnetic material OR NOT</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be stationary</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The conductor PQ is carrying a current I, which produces a magnetic field around it (as described by the right-hand rule: if you grasp the conductor with your right hand with the thumb pointing in the direction of the current, the fingers curl in the direction of the magnetic field). <br/>  <br/> The compass needle K is a small magnet that aligns itself with the net magnetic field at its location. Since the Earth's magnetic field is neglected, the only magnetic field present is due to the current in the conductor. <br/>  <br/> The magnetic field produced by the current-carrying conductor is fixed in direction at a given point (it circles around the wire). Therefore, the compass needle will align with this field and settle in a fixed direction. <br/>  <br/> This occurs regardless of whether the conductor PQ is magnetic or not. The magnetic field is due to the current, not the material of the conductor (as long as it is a conductor carrying current). <br/>  <br/> Thus, the correct option is: <br/>  <br/> \"settle in a fixed direction WHETHER the conductor PQ is a magnetic material OR NOT\"</div>", "topic": "MAGNETIC FIELD : FORCE ON A CURRENT-CARRYING CONDUCTOR"}, {"id": "objective>Physics>1989>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"position:relative;max-width:100%;\"/> <br/> A beam of radiation is passed between a pair of charged plates as indicated in the fig above. Beam P is undetected While Q is deflected to the left. P and Q respectively should be <br/>  <br/> I. γ-rays, β-rays <br/> II. x-rays, β-rays <br/> III. γ-rays, x-rays <br/> IV. x-rays, x-rays</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">III only</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I and II</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">III and IV</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Since beam P passes straight without deflection it must be neutral radiation such as γ-rays or X-rays, while beam Q is deflected towards the positive plate meaning it consists of negatively charged β-rays, hence the correct pairs are I and II.</div>", "topic": "ELEMENTARY MODERN PHYSICS : ALPHA, BETA AND GAMMA RAYS"}];
